  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Cheoyong
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Long winds drive the waves—silver halls tremble.
    Where cloud-brocade breaks, divine peaks pierce the sky.
    Auspicious light gathers, layered green in half the heavens,
    while river god and sea god press close from all sides.

    Among them stands one of terrible beauty—
    neither human, nor ghost, nor immortal of heaven's courts.
    Face ruddy-full, teeth white and sparse,
    shoulder sloped like a hawk, a robe of azure cloud half-draped.

    The cloud-robe flutters, fragrance rises on sudden wind,
    driven by celestial escort into halls of gold.
    Spring breeze ripples soft across the city walls;
    a thousand households bloom in moonlit peach and plum.

    Twisted sleeves of purple sweep and spin in pairs,
    flowers pinned at temples dance with every gust.
    Drunk and swaying, never ceasing in the dance,
    singing praises of the sacred virtue, praying for a thousand springs.

    Then that small spirit of plague—how petty was its pow'r!
    Yet reckless, it dared deception beyond measure,
    cheating heaven and earth—a crime without equal.
    Had it met a greater hand, it would have been cut down.

    Gye-rim's ancient days now fade like distant clouds;
    the sacred being departed, never to return.
    From Silla's time until this very day,
    all have vied to paint its face in finest detail,

    to ward off demons, to guard against all sickness—
    every new year's dawn, its image graces every gate.
    They sing its deeds and craft them into music;
    the melodies flow like the cry of phoenix fair:
    sorrowful yet not broken, joyful yet never base.

    Five dancers whirl their gauze sleeves face to face,
    ten thousand fingers blend with pipe and flute,
    while at night they lead the spirit-dancers in the palace,
    and what began in play became the year's great rite.

    The Lord smiled, commanded robes bestowed with grace;
    the dancers lined the hall in brilliant throng.
    I once held favor, stood before his throne,
    yet now two years have passed since I beheld that face.
    Watching this portrait, I cannot hold my tears—
    the sorrow of the aging poet falls like rain.
  footnotes:
    - Cheoyong is a legendary figure from the Silla dynasty, often depicted as a protective spirit against plague and evil. This poem, written by the Joseon scholar-official Seong Hyeon, commemorates the historical and cultural significance of this figure.
    - The 'fire spirit' (火精) and 'plague spirit' (疫神) refer to the epidemic demon that Cheoyong famously subdued or danced away according to legend.
    - The 'five dancers' and their performance represent the famous Cheoyong mask dance, which became an important ritual performance to ensure protection and good fortune.
    - The final verses reveal the poem's personal dimension—the aged poet reflects on having once served in the royal court, now distant from power, finding melancholy in memory.
